{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:31:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11580"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11580"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.27,0.22,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4209"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4209","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4209"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1144"},{"type":"tags","id":"2798"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13171"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of hoarseness. He has not had any recent respiratory tract infections. He has a medical history of hypertension and a 25 pack-year smoking history. His regular medications include amlodipine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination reveals smooth enlargement of the lower pole of the right lobe of the thyroid. Thyroid function tests are normal. An ultrasound is arranged, which shows a 3 cm solitary nodule in the right lobe of the thyroid, spongiform in appearance and with a smooth margin. The remainder of the gland appears normal. An ultrasound-guided fine needle aspiration is benign (Bethesda 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thyroid scintigraphy","Core needle biopsy","CT scan of the neck","Radioactive iodine uptake test","Fibreoptic laryngeal nasendoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient presenting with hoarseness, the possibility of malignancy must be considered. This patient\u0027s risk factors include his age, gender, and smoking history. While the thyroid nodule warrants investigation (and has already been performed), the possibility of laryngeal pathology, including cancer, needs to be evaluated. \u003Cstrong\u003EFibreoptic laryngeal nasendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it allows direct visualization of the larynx and vocal cords. This procedure can identify any laryngeal lesions or vocal cord paralysis that might be causing the hoarseness. It can also determine if there is any recurrent laryngeal nerve involvement from a potential thyroid malignancy, although this would be unlikely given the location of the nodule and the biopsy result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eradioactive iodine uptake test\u003C/strong\u003E measures thyroid function by assessing how much radioactive iodine is taken up by the thyroid 4-6 hours and 24 hours after ingestion. This is a diagnostic tool for thyroid disease but would not directly address the cause of hoarseness in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECore needle biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E involves taking a larger sample from the thyroid. While some studies suggest core needle biopsy is more accurate than fine needle aspiration (FNA), current recommendations in Australia support the use of FNA only. Since the FNA was benign, evaluating the larynx is required. For a Bethesda 2 nodule, ultrasound surveillance is still warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E is used as an adjunctive investigation for staging of head and neck cancers (thyroid or laryngeal). However, it is not the most appropriate next step before visualizing the larynx directly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E is nuclear imaging of the thyroid gland. It is typically used in patients with a low TSH, where increased uptake may suggest a hyperactive thyroid. In this case, with normal thyroid function tests, scintigraphy is not indicated as the next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter performing fibreoptic laryngeal nasendoscopy, further investigations such as a CT scan may be considered based on the findings. The priority is to evaluate the larynx to determine the cause of the patient\u0027s hoarseness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any patient with persisting unexplained voice hoarseness should be referred to an ENT surgeon for further investigation.","Clinical examination, including nasal endoscopy, is important to guide further investigations in patients with hoarseness.","Thyroid nodules and laryngeal pathology can both present with hoarseness, necessitating thorough evaluation of both possibilities."],"references":["Bailey S, Wallwork B. Differentiating between benign and malignant thyroid nodules. Australian Journal of General Practitioners. 2021;47(11):770-774. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/november/differentiating-between-benign-and-malignant-t-1","Lee J, Harris A, Khafagi F. Thyroid scans. Australian Family Physician. 2012;41(8):584-586. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/thyroid-scans","Pretorius P M, Milford C A. Investigating the hoarse voice BMJ 2008;337:a1726. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18842646/","Croker EE, McGrath SA, Rowe CW. Thyroid disease: Using diagnostic tools effectively. Australian journal of general practice. 2021 Feb 1;50(1/2):16-21. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/january-february/thyroid-disease-using-diagnostic-tools-effectively"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11580"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-28T16:19:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-28T16:19:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4209"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only s